{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496955"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:00:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:00:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1445"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1445"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.5,0.06,0.17,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1445"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104901"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1445"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1445"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87287"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"493"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7113"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7163"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12908"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37154"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42321"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43082"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104901"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of worsening shortness of breath. He has also noticed some palpitations, which he has been suffering for the past two weeks. His medical history includes chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), for which he is on tiotropium daily and uses PRN salbutamol regularly. He is a reformed smoker. On examination, his blood pressure is 128/70 mmHg, pulse 150/min, temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 20/min, and SpO2 95% on room air. Examination of his chest demonstrated prolonged expiration without a wheeze. An ECG is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["DC cardioversion","Non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker","Rapid atrial pacing","Valsalva Manoeuvres","Catheter ablation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA patient with a history of COPD and presenting with palpitations is very likely to have an arrhythmia. The ECG shows a typical sawtooth waveform consistent with atrial flutter; the flutter waves are best appreciated in V1 with regular atrial deflections, and variable conduction to the ventricle via the AV node.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe vital signs demonstrate the patient is haemodynamically stable, or at least maintaining an adequate blood pressure to not require urgent cardioversion. Therefore, he can be managed with medications. The first-line treatment for atrial flutter in a haemodynamically stable patient includes either rate control or rhythm control. Rate control can also be achieved with\u003Cstrong\u003E non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers\u003C/strong\u003E or beta blockers. Beta-blockers are relatively contraindicated in patients with COPD, such as this patient, because of a possible exacerbation. Rhythm control is preferred over rate control if the patient is young, has a new onset atrial fibrillation, failed rate control strategy or has an acute illness that precipitated the arrhythmia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERhythm control can be achieved by electrical or pharmacological (amiodarone, propafenone, flecainide, ibutilide etc) means. Rhythm control with \u003Cstrong\u003EDC cardioversion \u003C/strong\u003Eis utilised if the patient is haemodynamically unstable or has persistent atrial flutter despite adequate medical treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid atrial pacing \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be considered in patients who have recurrent supraventricular tachycardias (SVT). Since this is a first-time occurrence in this patient, this approach would not be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAtrial flutter can sometimes be confused with other regular narrow complex tachycardias, such as AV nodal re-entrant tachycardia (AVNRT). If there is any uncertainty in the diagnosis of atrial flutter, vagal manoeuvres such as\u003Cstrong\u003E Valsalva manoeuvres\u003C/strong\u003E or adenosine infusion can help slow the ventricular rate and unmask the atrial rhythm, confirming the diagnosis of atrial flutter. However, atrial flutter will not usually convert to sinus rhythm with these manoeuvres. In this case. A. Flutter is a clear diagnosis based on the ECG, performing multiple vagal manoeuvres will be of little benefit. On the other hand, they can be effective in converting AVNRT to sinus rhythm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECatheter ablation\u003C/strong\u003E is a long-term treatment in a patient with sustained or recurrent atrial tachy-arrythmias who has exhibited a failure to at least one concerted effort to medical treatment. This patient has never undergone long-term medical therapy for atrial flutter, so this will not be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Atrial flutter and fibrillation can develop in patients with COPD due to a number of reasons involving the disease itself or its treatment. The first line of treatment for atrial flutter in a haemodynamically stable patient with no contraindications is rate control with Nondihydropyridine calcium channel blocker.","Rhythm control is adopted in a patient who has a new onset atrial fibrillation, has failed rate control or is young. Rhythm control prevents ventricular remodelling."],"references":["Verma KP, Wong M. Atrial fibrillation. Aust J Gen Pract. 2019 Oct;48(10):694\u20139. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/october/atrial-fibrillation","Aggarwal, A., Jain, A., Hughes, K., Patel, M., Hamdon, M., \u0026amp; Kumar, S. (2020). Comparing efficacy and safety of verapamil versus Diltiazem in atrial fibrillation and flutter with rapid ventricular response. Journal of the American College of Cardiology, 75(11), 527. Available from: https://www.jacc.org/doi/10.1016/S0735-1097(20)31154-2"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87287"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1445"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18555"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18555"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/144ee23b-a726-445a-aaeb-c5462b9add68.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/144ee23b-a726-445a-aaeb-c5462b9add68.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":412}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87287"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-05T16:55:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-05T16:56:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1445"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104901"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"